<h2>Purpose</h2>
<p>
  Grounds decision <a href="/backlog/1470-selection-intent-optional-deselect-axis-for-single-select-al/">#1470</a> —
  should the <a href="/intents/selection/">selection intent</a> gain an
  <strong>optional deselect / &ldquo;allow no selection&rdquo;</strong> axis for
  <code>model:single</code>: the ability to return a chosen single-select group (radio, segmented,
  single-select menu) to the <em>empty</em> state? Native HTML radio cannot be user-unchecked — once a
  value is picked the user can switch options but never clear back to none. This is a
  <strong>greenfield axis</strong>: <code>selection.json</code> exposes only
  <code>model</code>/<code>immediacy</code>/<code>variant</code>/<code>grouping</code> (plus a
  <code>constraints?{min,max}</code> type in its interface block) and <em>no</em> nullability
  dimension, so this survey precedes the forks.
</p>

<h2>The platform codifies the inverse axis, not this one</h2>
<p>
  Native radio <strong>cannot</strong> be returned to an all-unchecked state by the user (MDN
  <code>radiogroup</code>: once checked, &ldquo;it is not possible to return to having no radio buttons
  checked&rdquo;). The WAI-ARIA APG radio pattern only asserts mutual exclusivity. The one axis ARIA
  <em>does</em> codify is <code>aria-required</code> — the <em>opposite</em> of optional. The platform's
  &ldquo;single choice that can be empty&rdquo; idiom lives in the <strong>listbox/<code>&lt;select&gt;</code></strong>
  family (a placeholder/empty <code>&lt;option&gt;</code>), not the radio family — and Open UI's
  customizable-select inherits that lineage with no standardized <code>clearable</code> semantic yet.
</p>

<h2>The pattern is established, but family-split</h2>
<ul>
  <li>
    <strong>Toggle / segmented / chip — default-ON.</strong> Radix
    <code>ToggleGroup type="single"</code> deselects on re-activate <em>by default</em>, with a boolean
    that disables it to &ldquo;always keep a value selected after first selection.&rdquo; Mantine
    <code>Select</code> ships <code>allowDeselect</code> (default <code>true</code>).
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Dropdown / listbox — opt-in clear button.</strong> Ant Design <code>allowClear</code>
    renders an explicit &ldquo;x&rdquo; affordance.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Native radio — absent.</strong> React Aria and Chakra reach the none-state only
    <em>programmatically</em> (<code>value: null</code> / <code>onChange('')</code>), never via a
    built-in user gesture.
  </li>
</ul>

<h2>Naming — a named boolean, never a count-constraint</h2>
<p>
  Every implementation names this a <strong>boolean axis</strong>: <code>allowDeselect</code> (clearing
  via the control's own items — WE's case), <code>allowClear</code> (the dropdown x-button), or the
  inverse <code>required</code>/<code>isRequired</code>. <strong>No</strong> surveyed library models it
  as a count-constraint (<code>min:0</code>) on a single-select control — that framing only appears for
  multi-select selection counts. This argues for a named dimension on the intent over folding it into
  <code>constraints.min</code>.
</p>

<h2>Trigger is renderer packaging, not intent vocabulary</h2>
<p>
  For the radio/segmented shape the dominant trigger is <strong>re-activate the already-selected
  item</strong>; the dropdown idiom is an &ldquo;x&rdquo; button. Escape is <em>not</em> a value-clear
  convention. Which gesture clears is impl/keyboard detail (a fixed mechanic per #1440) — confirming the
  intent should express <em>that</em> a single-select can be cleared, not <em>how</em>.
</p>

<h2>Recommendation seed</h2>
<p>
  Model the axis as a <strong>named boolean dimension</strong>, <strong>default-permissive</strong>
  (deselect allowed) per the <a href="/intents/">most-flexible-default</a> principle, with
  &ldquo;require a value&rdquo; as the author's opt-in — the permissive complement of
  <code>required</code>, matching Radix <code>ToggleGroup</code>'s default-deselectable + disable model.
</p>

